But the school argued that the wedding did not warrant time off because it could not be classed as ‘exceptional circumstances’.

The couple, who have been together for three years, are now facing a criminal prosecution and believe their wedding pictures might be used in court to prove Riley’s unauthorised absence from school.

Speaking as the couple posed for photos after their ceremony, Clare said: 'These pictures might get me sent to prison but, frankly, I don’t care.

'This is one of the happiest days of my life and I wanted Riley here beside me.'

Riley, who lives with his mother and step-father Mr McLeary added: 'I don’t like missing school but I wouldn’t miss seeing her get married for the world.

'I'm chuffed to bits to be part of my mum's big day. I enjoyed throwing the confetti on her and Andy.

